summary:
The Security Council,
Reaffirming previous resolutions and statements on Somalia, particularly resolution 733 (1992) which established an arms embargo, 
Reaffirming Somalia's sovereignty, territorial integrity, political independence, and unity,
 Reiterating the need for Somali leaders to engage in political dialogue,
 Supporting the Special Representative of the Secretary-General,
 Stressing the need for effective national governance,
 Commending African Union and Intergovernmental Authority on Development efforts,
 Noting the report of the Monitoring Group (S/2006/229),
 Condemning the increase in weapons and ammunition supplies to Somalia, 
 Concerned about piracy and armed robbery off Somalia's coast,
 Insisting on compliance with the arms embargo,
 Determining the situation in Somalia threatens international peace and security,
 Acting under Chapter VII,
1. Stresses all Member States' obligation to comply with resolution 733 (1992);
2. Intends to consider actions to improve implementation of the arms embargo;
3. Requests the Secretary-General to re-establish the Monitoring Group for six months with the mandate to: 
(a) Continue tasks outlined in resolution 1587 (2005);
(b) Investigate revenue sources used for arms embargo violations;
(c) Investigate transport, routes, and facilities used for arms embargo violations;
(d) Update the list of individuals and entities violating the arms embargo;
(e) Make recommendations based on investigations;
(f) Work with the Committee on additional measures to improve compliance;
(g) Identify areas to strengthen States' capacities in the region to implement the arms embargo.
The Security Council:

3. Requests the Monitoring Group to:
(h) provide a midterm briefing to the Council through the Committee within 90 days of its establishment;
(i) submit a final report covering all tasks to the Security Council through the Committee no later than 15 days prior to the termination of its mandate;

4. Requests the Secretary-General to make necessary financial arrangements to support the Monitoring Group's work;

5. Reaffirms paragraphs 4, 5, 7, 8, and 10 of resolution 1519 (2003);

6. Requests the Committee to consider the Monitoring Group's report and recommend ways to improve implementation of and compliance with the arms embargo;

7. Requests the Committee to consider a visit to Somalia and/or the region by its Chairman and designated members;

8. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
